i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are helpless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

trump is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still is that republicans willingly piggybacked this lunacy while campaigning for the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason

trump is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still is that republicans willingly piggybacked this lunacy while campaigning for the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

text:
a #hartwell man was arrested this week for allegedly raping a 5-year-old girl.
.
irun robinson, 21, was arrested on tuesday after investigations by the police connected him to a rape case of a minor on nov. 14.
.
#robinson, who is the prime #suspect in the case, is said to have had prior offences. he was sentenced to 22months for breaking and entering in 2015 when he was just 18 and later transferred to volunteers for #america to complete is sentence but escaped the facility in #2016
.
robinson was recaptured and pleaded guilty to escape in #march of this year, getting another sentence of nine months in #prison.
.
robinson is now being held on a $100,000 bond at the #hamilton county #justice center awaiting trial for the #rape of the 5-year-old victim.
.
.
#rapevictim#stoprape #endrapeculture #domesticviolence
#domesticviolenceawareness#pedophile #molestation #metoo #nomeansno

text:
i love men. always will, always have.

because of my rather difficult relationship with women sometimes i gravitated easily towards friendships with men. i love their precisiveness, the focus they have (without getting lost in the details like i love doing) and their amazing advice. 
this year seemed to have been the general men bashing year. my feeds were all about surpression of women by men and the #metoo movement that highlighted a very important fact of what women have to deal with but it also made all men look like they are egotistical, narcassistic a**holes.

now, i am not here to tell you that you can't have that opinion but i refuse to jump on that train of negativity.

yes, i have had my fair share of heart breaks and sexual harrassment. but i also had horrible experiences where women betrayed my trust and hurt me deeply. i turned things around and instead of feeling like a victim i asked myself: how can i learn from the situation and avoid these situations in the future? 
we will always have duality in life and there will always be good people and people who we consider 'bad' for not playing according to our rules and that won't change!

but together we are stronger.
together we can compliment each other with our own, unique strengths.

and thankfully i have lot of men in my life who are kind-hearted, supportive and willing to learn.

this current era is not easy for men nor women. we are all re-defining who we are. i, for my part, want to live in peace with the opposite sex and don't need fighting, finger-pointing (on the past) and wanting to be right at any cost. my life is too short and instead of concentrating on this i rather help my clients become the best version of themselves and live a balanced, happy life â¤ï¸
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
#confidencecoachingforwomen #balance #men #oppositesattract #wecomplimenteachother #duality #beuniquelyyou

text:
nama scott gelb menjadi sorotan utama dalam permasalahan ini, karena ketika investigasi dan wawancara mendalam yang dilakukan oleh kotaku,  8 bulan sebelum artikel tentang kasus ini terbit agustus tahun ini, namanya paling sering muncul. ia dituding acap kali melakukan pelecehan seksual sepertinya secara tidak sopan dengan menyentuh karyawan laki-laki atau perempuan hingga kentut didekat wajah mereka.â €
.â €
menyewa lembaga hukum seyfarth shaw untuk melakukan investigasi, akhirnya riot games menetapkan hukuman kepada coo mereka. melalui email yang dikirimkan kepada seluruh karyawan minggu ini, riot ceo nicolo laurent mengindikasikan bahwa banyak investigasi internal yang tidak bisa dipublikasikan kepada publik, namun mengingat posisi gelb di perusahaan, board of director ingin hukuman kepada gelb dipublikasi dengan jelas.â €
.â €
dalam email tersebut juga, laurent mengatakan banyak tuduhan kepada gelb tidaklah benar. namun tidak dijelaskan investigasi mana atau tuduhan apa yang tidak benar kepada  gelb. hukuman yang didapat oleh gelb tidaklah berat, apalagi di era #metoo sekarang ini, dimana tidak sedikit petinggi perusahaan yang harus kehilangan jabatannya akibat perilaku seksual yang dilakukannya di tempat kerja.â €
â €

menyewa lembaga hukum seyfah shaw untuk melakukan investigasi, akhirnya riot games menetapkan hukuman kepada coo mereka. melalui email yang dikirimkan kepada seluruh karyawan minggu ini, riot ceo nicolo laurent mengindikasikan bahwa banyak investigasi internal yang tidak bisa dipublikasikan kepada publik, namun mengingat posisi gelb di perusahaan, board of director ingin hukuman kepada gelb dipublikasi dengan jelas.â €
.â €
dalam email tersebut juga, laurent mengatakan banyak tuduhan kepada gelb tidaklah benar. namun tidak dijelaskan investigasi mana atau tuduhan apa yang tidak benar kepada  gelb. hukuman yang didapat oleh gelb tidaklah berat, apalagi di era  sekarang ini, dimana tidak sedikit petinggi perusahaan yang harus kehilangan jabatannya akibat perilaku seksual yang dilakukannya di tempat kerja.â €
â €

text:
gerty theresa cori (august 15, 1896 â€“ october 26, 1957) was a jewish austrian-american biochemist who became the third womanâ€”and first american womanâ€”to win a nobel prize in science, and the first woman to be awarded the nobel prize in physiology or medicine, in 1947, for her role in the discovery of glycogen metabolism.
gerty was not a nickname, but rather she was named after an austrian warship.
growing up at a time when women were marginalized in science and allowed few educational opportunities, she gained admittance to medical school, where she met her future husband carl ferdinand cori; upon their graduation in 1920, they married.
because of deteriorating conditions in europe, the couple emigrated to the united states in 1922.
gerty cori continued her early interest in medical research, collaborating in the laboratory with carl.
she published research findings coauthored with her husband, as well as publishing singly.
unlike her husband, she had difficulty securing research positions, and the ones she obtained provided meager pay.
her husband insisted on continuing their collaboration, though he was discouraged from doing so by the institutions that employed him.
with her husband carl and argentine physiologist bernardo houssay, gerty cori received the nobel prize in 1947 for the discovery of the mechanism by which glycogenâ€”a derivative of glucoseâ€”is broken down in muscle tissue into lactic acid and then resynthesized in the body and stored as a source of energy (known as the cori cycle).
they also identified the important catalyzing compound, the cori ester.
in 2004, both gerty and carl cori were designated a national historic chemical landmark in recognition of their work in clarifying carbohydrate metabolism.
in 1957, gerty cori died after a ten-year struggle with myelosclerosis.
she remained active in the research laboratory until the end.
cori was honored by the release of a us postal service stamp in april, 2008.
the us department of energy named the nersc-8 supercomputer installed in 2015/2016 after cori.

text:
since the banning of "baby its cold outside" in light of the #metoo movement, please boycott the christmas song "i want a hippopotamus for christmas" because it exploits endangered hippos.

while we are at it the same goes for: "santa clause is coming to town" = fake news "little drummer boy" = gender neutral "white christmas" = racist and xenophobic "o' come all ye faithful" = exclusive "god rest ye merry gentlemen" = anti-feminist "all i want for christmas is you" = stalking "blue christmas" = implies male/boy righteousness "the 12 days of christmas" = anti-semitic (8 days) "santa baby" = reverse #metoo and exploits handouts "winter wonderland" = dismisses wonderlands that don't have winter "its the most wonderful time of the year" = exclusive against 4th of july and summer "let it snow" = not fair to those where it does not snow "do you hear what i hear" = insensitive to hearing impaired "all i want for christmas is my two front teeth" = offensive to meth addicts

and last but not least.... "i saw mommy kissing santa claus" = promotes adultery

if this offends anyone, please donâ€™t bother to tell me as i just donâ€™t care. i drink coffee stronger coffee stronger than your feelings. ğŸ˜‚ğŸ‘ğŸ¼ğŸ˜˜

text:
@semspeshawar held an event to encourage women entrepreneurs in kp last week. i was at the event as a panelist to discuss the challenges and opportunities for women in #kpk in the next five years. it was a good effort by sems but something bothered me big time.
a young school girl had a question about harassment and she was told by one of the panelist that if you stay within the limits of 'haya' and 'islam' you won't be harassed. by then i had stepped off the discussion forum and wasn't in a position to question it. but that was wrong on so many levels. it's a prime example of how our society blames the victim. i wanted to ask the respected lady to wear a burqa and then go travel on public transport and see how her pardah saves her from harassment.

i personally feel,  dressing up provocatively may invite extra harassment but dressing modestly doesn't actually save you from what is already out there. 
views?

#harrassment #victimblaming #sexualharrasment #women #eomenempowerment #girlboss #girlbosses #metoo

text:
12-wie of wat heb je in 2018 losgelaten?
ik liet los dat je een bedrijf runnen en reizen eigenlijk niet goed kunt combineren. dat kan dus wel. sommige plannen waar ik te lang aan vast hield liet ik los, zoals: ik moet een onlineprogramma aanbieden, nee, ik moet aanbieden wat ik leuk vind en ik ben nu eenmaal die coach die het liefst persoonlijk en op maat werkt. ik liet het idee los dat ik vooral lachende selfies moet maken voor social media liefst vol in de make-up en in een jurk en #lovemyjoblovemylife teksten moet hashtaggen ;) (nee, lieve mensen, ik heb nog steeds geen mooie beeldbank met glamourfotoâ€™s, komt misschien nog wel ;) ik ben toch echt meer een wandelschoentype die soms in een jurk loopt.
.
de gedachte dat ik in gezelschap niet moet laten merken dat ik veel van voetballen weet (want ik heb daar gewoon verstand van :). de twijfel of ik me wel of niet zou uitspreken over #metoo. wel dus. mijn hoogtevrees kon ik behoorlijk loslaten; na jaren eindelijk aangepakt en actie ondernomen. dat ik me zou moeten aanpassen qua spirituele beleving en taal (want die beleef ik op mijn manier en in mijn eigen taal en die wijkt af van wat ik om me heen zie en lees en veel ervan zegt me ook helemaal niets.)
.
ik heb losgelaten (en eigenlijk nooit aangenomen) dat ik iets zou moeten veranderen omdat je, als je vijftig wordt, vanuit de buitenwereld ineens de boodschap krijgt dat er â€˜ietsâ€™ moet veranderen in je leven, gezien de folders in de bus, ja, ze weten je ineens te vinden. wtf?! waarom?! ik vind mezelf helemaal niet oud en meestal jonger van geest dan sommige leeftijdsgenoten. zo. .
een assessment psycholoog zei ooit tegen me: u bent heel evenwichtig. daar baalde ik van want dat stond voor mij gelijk aan: boooring! saai! suf! nu, dÃ¡t heb ik dus ook losgelaten. laat mij maar gewoon evenwichtig zijn en mâ€™n eigen gang gaan zonder extreme uitschieters. :) en jij, wie of wat heb jij losgelaten? .
(foto: real madrid wint de champions league en daar genoot ik van! uren staan wachten tot de bus met spelers langs kwam maar het was het waard).

text:
lady her talk (lady's sparrow foundation, presented by lady's sparrow foundation, is breaking the silence around women's sexual health and building a community for women to heal, empower, and reclaim their bodies.come join us for a fireside chat with sexual health experts and learn more about our sexual health and the resources available while building your tribe of supportive women.

women's sexual health is complex and trusted resources are hard to find. learn more about everything from sexual pain to dysfunction, sex after pregnancy to sex after menopause, low libido to hyper libido, and sex and relationship. there will be a q&a to follow to ask those questions you've been too embarrassed to ask in an supportive and judgement free environment.

#silentnomore #powerofher #ladyssparrow #metoo #womenempowerment
#womenleaders #women
#womenssexuality
#sexualhealth #bravery
#breakingthestigma

#repost via @cnn - cyntoia brown, who's serving life in prison for killing a man who bought her for sex when she was 16, could still be freed soon.
the tennessee supreme court last week ruled brown would have to serve at least 51 years in prison for the 2004 killing before she's eligible for release.
but amid widespread outrage on social media, gov. bill haslam's office is now reviewing her case. <â€”â€”- proof that we can have a voice and impact. â€”â€”-
what to do now? 
1. go read about the case
2. sign the moveon petition 
3. share your thoughts and links on social media so folks know and can take action 
4. contact gov bill haslamâ€™s office and voice your thoughts 1st floor, state capitol nashville, tn 37243 (615) 741-2001 
5. his instagram @governorbillhaslam (remember, he is considering clemency so letâ€™s honor and encourage that) 
6. watch the video: me facing life: cyntoiaâ€™s story - google it - itâ€™s on @pbs and you can watch it online. â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”

text:
â€œforgiveness and reconciliation are two different things, miri. forgiveness is a choice. it happens in an instant. reconciliation is a journey. it may take you the rest of your life. but forgiveness must come first.â€
.
#read #104 of 2018: everything is wonderful by chelsea marcantel
.
at the age of twenty, miri was shunned by her amish family and community and forced to leave her homestead. in the wake of a familial tragedy, she returns to find that the ghosts of her past are still very much alive and that, for some, righteously held beliefs are thicker than blood.
.
a quiet yet steady drama for 3f, 3m. spoiler: another appropriate play in the #metoo era, though told from a perspective we donâ€™t often see in new, 21st century plays.
.
would definitely recommend for high schools, community theatres, and colleges. there is a great dramatic monologue for miri and great scenework (especially for 1f, 1m) throughout.
.

text:
itâ€™s easy to make things look pretty (hello instagram) but reality is what iâ€™m looking for. after listening to speakers and collaborating with my teams, i know one thing is true. we want truth. we want real.

gen z and millennials want to know reality more than pretty words, sugar coated messages and smiles that donâ€™t go away.

truth is, there is hurt and pain all around us. #metoo #churchtoo.

the inside critic says donâ€™t share. donâ€™t post. donâ€™t frown. but freedom says, who cares what they say. let your voice be heard.

shout loud your thoughts, feelings, hurts, injustices.

shout loud your passion, your anger, your opinions.

in love, letâ€™s wrap our arms around each other in a world full of broken pieces, broken hearts. let judgement be far from our lips and let the critic inside us all be silenced.

be brave to tell your story. forget the appearance of it all. let your heart be heard.

let us all be led to light.

text:
so, time for some thoughts...
last night, i went over to someoneâ€™s house. letâ€™s call him cory. this was supposed to be a chance to get to know one another, and see how we mesh as people. what it ended up being is me, lying in a bed terrified of saying â€œnoâ€ because i was scared of what heâ€™d do. any requests or attempts to redirect the situation were pushed past or completely ignored. he was coercive and manipulative, bouncing between tender, kind, controlling, hungry, angry, and a myriad of other emotions. iâ€™ve never been in a position where i was legitimately scared to say â€œnoâ€ as he dragged my hands where he wanted them to go.
to him, i was just a body, a delicious lay that he could sink his teeth into. he felt entitled to me, and made it evident that i was being unfair to him if i rejected his advances. he even tried to get me to have one of my partners come over once he found out they were physically his type. it got so bad i started crying, sobbing uncontrollably as i attempted to drag my pants back up my legs. instead of comforting me, he just told me to stop, and when i didnâ€™t, he huffed over to my purse and dropped it next to me. â€œcall your bfâ€ he told me. 
iâ€™d never been in this position before, unable to escape and watching everything i say in case it set him off...he never hit me, instead he made it very clear that he was in charge and it was in my best interest to cooperate.
the whole encounter was awful, but it reminded me that people are very different online, and men will often say whatever they need to as long as it gets them what they want. 
i know a lot of this encounter was my fault, but that doesnâ€™t justify his actions.
hell of a learning curve.
#metoo

text:
#metooinmedicine

i never shared my story. why? for the reason that many other women failed to share- fear of retaliation, fear of perception, fear of professional harm - fear. furthermore, we all know medicine seems to lag about 20 years behind the rest of the world in social advancement.

my eyes were truly opened today at a watch (women at childrenâ€™s national) seminar on sexual harassment in the work place. 
i am still quite low on the totem pole - i am in my 3rd year as an attending and assistant professor at a large academic hospital. yes, i am an attending, i am a professor, i do have grant funding - but the fact is i still have (hopefully) another 30-40 years left of my career in academic medicine. 
for that reason, when the rest of the world was sharing their #metoo stories - you may have noticed the women and men in medicine remaining relatively silent (with a few exceptions of course!). throughout my 18 years having an md by my name, i (most often unknowingly) was the brunt of sexism and what i now know is deemed sexual harassment. but i never spoke up. as we further specialize into our ultimate careers - it becomes incredibly apparent that our career communities become smaller and smaller. that fear of being the â€œoutspokenâ€ male or female keeps most of us quiet. this needs to end. as i write this i can remember innumerable side comments on my looks, my size, societal norms of being a woman, being â€œcuteâ€ - let me tell the world - when i am at work i am not â€œcute.â€ i am a badass pediatric critical care attending, i command a room when i am taking care of critically ill children, and i hustled to get grant funding less than 2 years into being an attending. the more we speak out, the more we force the culture of medicine to catch up to the rest of the world. .
i would like to say that i am very happy in my current job. i have a boss that supports me and i have colleagues that lift me up. but it wasnâ€™t always this way. and that needs to change. 
so whatâ€™s your stance on #metooinmedicine ? are we ready for change? share your opinion, your stance or even your stories.

text:
ego - someone's ego is their sense of their own worth. for example, if someone has a large ego, they think they are very important and valuable.

we all have a sense of self worth. for better or worse, it is important that we realize how much we are worth to those around us. but when does it become a problem? when does our sense of self worth turn into self-importance and self centeredness? 
is your ego affecting people around you in a positive way? or is it self serving only to you? are you so self-centered that you will do anything to stroke that ego. even if it means crushing the self worth of those you come into contact with?

in my career as a model, this was an everyday experience. the men and even sometimes women in this industry were egotistical, and self serving. the drive to fulfill their own desires was the only goal. if you were collateral damage, so be it. -

you see, your ego is the justifier to your actions. one more time.... your ego is the justifier to your actions! you can justify anything you do if it pleases your ego. a photographer will mentally, sexually, verbally abuse a model. but ego tells him/her itâ€™s part of the artistic process. an agent will knowingly and willingly put a model in a compromised position. but the ends justify the means, or at least thatâ€™s what ego tells them. there are many more instances in this arena, but itâ€™s not exclusive only to fashion/modeling. -

my self-worth during my time modeling was at an all time low. i wasnâ€™t the same person that i was going into it. years of being broken down to serve others egos took its toll on me. i compensated, for a low self-worth and projected my ego onto those around me. often not caring how it affected them. this is something i have worked on. keeping my self-esteem high but my ego in check. -

nobodyâ€™s ego is important enough to trample on anotherâ€™s sense of self. nobody is so above the rest that consequences from their actions shouldnâ€™t matter. how you treat people has ripple effects in this world. how has your ego affected those around you?

truth is inevitable.

#model #modeling #fashion #speakup #metoo #mentoo #timesup #modelalliance #selfworth #ego #love #mentalhealth

this week has been an off week. Â i had things come up and i didnâ€™t get to the store to stock up on my veggies and fruit. Â i find it amazing at the difference this made in my mood, energy levels and overall functioning. Â i had my powder version on hand that i usually use when traveling. Â it was ok, but not the same as the real deal.

i like to think of my green juice as my magic elixir. Â i feel better when i am regularly drinking it. Â my green juice is real simple - cucumbers, celery, granny smith apples, arugula, and ginger root. Â although it is simple, it contains approximately 6-7 servings of veggies and fruit. Â of course i feel great after drinking it - iâ€™m providing my body with essential energy needs. Â and, sometimes i choose to make up a green juice instead of having chocolate (shhh...donâ€™t tell anyone!). when we begin to take care of ourselves, our bodies feel it. text:
you gotta love josephâ€™s story!
â€œfrom slave to the ruler of egypt in 7 simple stepsâ€

here is his cv:

1-17 years old: favorite son of his father, jacob. his 10 brothers hate him.

17 yo: brothers want to kill him, but instead sell him as a slave to random nomads.

potiphar, a minister of the pharaoh, buys him and lets him slave away in his house. everything joseph does there is crowned by divine success.

28 yo: joseph is a handsome man and potipharâ€™s wife repeatedly tries to seduce him, but joseph is righteous and doesnâ€™t touch what is not his.

as revenge, potipharâ€™s wife joins the #metoo movement and accuses him of sexual harassment. 
following the #ibelieveher ideology, where a woman is to be believed anything she says against a man, without proof or evidence (isnâ€™t that sexist?), joseph is thrown into prison.

in his late 20â€™s joseph imagines his career to be somewhat different than sitting in a dark dungeon, but doesnâ€™t lose faith and uses his skills to become the prison wardenâ€™s right-hand #career #milennials

30 yo: pharaoh has dreams which nobody can interpret. joseph can. he predicts 7 years of plenty following 7 years of famine. 
pharaoh appoints him as his right-hand. he becomes the second man in egypt, the center of human civilization of that time.

joseph develops an economical scheme to prevent worldwide famine. #logistics #publicpolicy

39: joseph is #rich&famous. reigns over egypt with the pharaoh. 
his brothers come to egypt to buy food. 
he forgives his brothers, not without playing a little game on them before. ğŸ‘‰ğŸ» isnâ€™t it exciting how every scenario is already in the torah? that is why itâ€™s not a history book, but a blueprint for a fulfilling life.

have a great week, everybody!

text:
when i first recognized that i could use creativity as a tool to tell segments of my story, it created the most incredible and illuminating shift in my world. for the first time in my life, i felt as though i had an outlet. a way of expressing myself.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
this form of expression didn't change my circumstances. it didn't magically make all of my hurts disappear. but i felt as though the next breath was slightly less jagged. i finally had a coping mechanism. a hand held out. a friend.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
photography and creative writing have been lifelines for me. a way of giving a voice to some of my experiences, without the pressure of having to explain them. because explanation often requires justification, and then something is lost, further crushed inside.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
there are so many ways in which women are censored. we edit our existence because the world is still not ready to accept our multitudes. creativity helps to soften that editing process; it gives us a cloak of protection whilst also allowing us to be bare.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €

on december 17 at judson memorial church, we remember sex workers who have died from violence. international day to end violence against sex workers was founded 15 years ago in san francisco by @anniesprinkled as a memorial and candlelight vigil for the victims of the seattle green river killer. the day calls attention to hate crimes committed against sex workers worldwide, as well as the need to remove the stigma, discrimination and indifference that contributes to violence against them. it is now observed globally in local vigils and gatherings. 
from the time i began my career in human sexuality, the rights of sex workers has been my passion. in 1985, a meeting took place at judson memorial church that connected me with margo st. james and the international sex workersâ€™ rights movement. i have been active in that movement ever since. judson memorial church has been a long-time advocate for harm reduction and safe haven for sex workers, and the welcoming host of the nyc december 17 vigil for nearly a decade. i invite you to join me, members of judson, the sex worker community, and friends and allies as we remember the dead. rest in power.

you are welcome to participate in part or all of the eveningâ€™s events:

5pm -- the candle inscription and community-building session begins

7pm -- the open mic begins; reading of names, stories, songs, poetry and performances are encouraged.

9pm -- clean-up promptly begins

let us know if you want to be on the program and/or have relevant announcements, names and stories for us to honor and uplift on that day. 
more details about the nyc vigil are on our facebook page: 
http://bit.ly/dec17nyc2018

details about other global events are available at www.december17.org 
veronica vera
doctor of human sexuality

text:
the hindu reports 
the third edition of the likho awards for excellence in media were presented on saturday, right after the second edition of the likho indian lgbtq media summit.
the awards in 10 categories covered print and digital journalism along with graphic art, film, radio, and advertising.

some of the winners were journalists alka dhupkar, chitra palekar, roshan kokane and r. raj rao. filmmaker onir won for his 2005 filmÂ my brother nikhilÂ in a new category â€” the trailblazer â€” to honour an individualâ€™s past works.

preceding the awards ceremony was the likho indian lgbtq media summit with four panels: â€˜pitching lgbtq storiesâ€™ on queer roles in film and television; â€˜cracking the regional media codeâ€™ to encourage cross-pollination of thoughts; â€˜#lgbtqinmedia â€“ being an out media personâ€™ with several professionals recounting their experiences; and finally â€˜beyond #metoo â€“ creating equal, diverse, inclusive and safe media work places in indiaâ€™. three months after the supreme court partially struck down section 377, decriminalising homosexuality, the conclave sought to draw awareness to the road ahead for the queer community. ashok row kavi, chairperson of the humsafar trust, focused on the atmosphere pre and post the verdict. media professional dipti agarwal noted how newsrooms have changed, while priya babu of the transgender resource network highlighted the issues of the trans community and called for a change in its representation in the media. journalist and politician apsarra reddy said, â€œfor me, it is important to put my skill set and my talent out there. if people continue to judge me because of my gender, itâ€™s their problem.â€ she continued, â€œto reclaim your space is very important and in the whole #metoo movement, women need to have a stronger voice.â€ the event also hosted a screening of short filmÂ cover storyÂ by director suhail abbasi. the day-long event was organised byÂ bombay dost, indiaâ€™s oldest lgbtq magazine and the humsafar trust in partnership with blued, a gay social networking app. the summit was organised to promote a fair and inclusive workplace for the lgbtq community.
#journalist #mumbai #india #lgbtq #life #work #award

text:
if someone in your life has experienced sexual trauma, then you may struggle with what to say and how to help that #survivor . you may also struggle with understanding certain parts of their story, or how they are dealing with it.
.
those thoughts and feelings are very common.
.
there is a page on my website called "how to support a survivor" to help you navigate this journey.
.
the words and actions of those in a survivor's life have a huge impact on that survivor and their healing. you have a vitally important role to play. click the link in my bio, select "supporters of #metoo survivors" and then scroll down for some resources to help you.
.
share this post with anyone you know who is trying to figure out how to help a survivor.
.
.
.

text:
âœ¨ you might have noticed, i do think that digital activism can have an impact in real life but everyone does not agree!
â¡ï¸ for my last post for #digipoluclouvain, i wanted to share some of the critics made on digital activism.
ğŸ”¹ some people use the term â€œslacktivismâ€ to talk about cyber-activism. slacktivism is the contraction between â€œslackerâ€ and â€œactivismâ€ and it means that digital activism would actually be only clicks done by lazy people [40]. some people even argue that slacktivism could be â€œharmful to the larger process of civic renewalâ€ [41]. digital activism could be dangerous because it is only seen as actions made by individuals and not anymore as a collective protest, so the impact would be less effective [42].
ğŸ”¹ another critic made by peter levine is that cyber-activism can make a change but not in the long-term : â€œonline campaigns may all prove evanescent and lack an ability to handle and overcome valid criticisms or lack the infrastructure necessary to invite and train youth from apolitical networks to replace current leaders the way traditional political organizations could.â€ [43]
ğŸ”¹ a third critic is that it is not easy to evaluate the impact of cyber-activism [44].
â–ªï¸ i will argue by asking is it really easier to evaluate the impact of offline activism? some offline campaignsâ€™ impact can be measured (the civic right movement for example) as online campaignsâ€™ impact (#metoo) can be too.
â–ªï¸ thinking about that, i will also say that it depends on what activists ask for. during the civil rights movement, black people were demanding formal rights the states refused to give them [45]. but #metoo or #blacklivesmatter do not per se ask for formal rights, because violence is already punished by the law, equality between gender is already inscribed in the law [46]. what #metoo, #blacklivesmatter and many other movements ask nowadays is mostly a change of mentality, which can be slow and hard to measure.

text:
"remember when they told you i was too black for ya?
and now my black poppin' like a bra-strap on ya
i was kicked out, said i'm too loud
kicked out, said i'm too proud
but all i really ever felt was stressed out
kinda like my afro when it's pressed out" -janell monÃ¡e

in highschool (before it was cool) i didn't participate in the national anthem or pledge of allegiance,
i refused to speak lies and i knew not everyone was free.
and still to this day we are not free.
we as in you and me.

this is 2018
women are still being assaulted/raped and faulted for what they wear or don't wear and do.
black people are at fault and punished for being black.
immigrants are treated like trash.
gays can't even buy cakes.
so when are we free?
let's aim for 2019.
let's come together in solidarity.
let's end this foolishness.
let's be free like for real.
i am here to tell you, you cannot hate me for being black but you can hate me for me.
if you cannot control your penis, you must control your penis because you cannot control me.
if you can't stand to look at a gay couple look for compassion. 
and if you are assaulted for any or all of the above you were not asking for it and you don't deserve it.
if hate is what drives you;

drive somewhere else. âœŒï¸ because #wematter

text:
book #7
frances e. mascia-lees & nancy johnson black â€˜gender and anthropologyâ€™
2000

academicâ€”each of the nine chapters feels like a weekâ€™s lesson plans for a 10 week lecture courseâ€”it is a good starting point and very worth your time read in the #metoo era; despite the brevity each section is packed with information and thoughtful explanation of many theories by numerous anthropologist.

you learn to think for yourself by having multiple sources in-part that in-total add up to the possible truth (no one theory can tell us why our society or any society is the way it is, or why women, minorities, and non-western peoples are represented/discussed/treated the way they have been). critical thinking skills are honed in this (as a first foray into gender studies â€˜gender and anthropologyâ€™ is for many readersâ€™ the first steps into an understanding of why humanityâ€™s many cultures, historical and contemporary, have and maintain its view of women, their importance in society, and their role within it.

by the time you arrive at chapter six it dawns on you that no one theory single-handedly is an easy explanation for cross-culture explanation for gender roles; all of these theories in part yet combined tell the story of why we are the way we are.

there is no single easy fitâ€”although friedrich engels comes close (centuries before the rest of euro-centric â€œcivilizationâ€ caught-up). one of my university course reads i neglected finishingâ€”but still managed to earn an a in the class. donâ€™t follow my lead. read books at the time you get them. so a years later you donâ€™t have finish as part of your list of â€œthe books that got awayâ€. #mybookclubfor1 #10000bookbucketlistchallenge #greatamericanread #whattoread #bookworm #genderstudies

text:
in 1877 two committed teachers and a dedicated student made history in chile!â €
.Â â €
when isabel lebrun and antonia tarragÃ³ founded two schools for girls in the xix century, they faced a major challenge: girls were not allowed to go to university in chile. no matter how well their students performed, their education would have to end with high school. and so, these two teachers fought and lobbied until the amunategui decree was passed in 1877, giving finally all women the right to attend university. their students could go to college. â €
now, a monument stands in downtown santiago to honor the lives, work and contribution of these two incredible teachers.â €
.â €
it would take another 10 years for the first woman to graduate university. eloisa diaz had studied in isabel lebrun's school and aspired to tear down barriers. when the amunategui decree was passed she enrolled in university but, because of prejudices at the time, had to attend classes with her mother. still, she persisted and in 1887 she became the first woman in chile to obtain a university degree. eloisa diaz was the first female doctor not just in chile but in all of latin america.Â â €
.â €
the feminist history of santiago and chile is rich and full of stories like that of isabel lebrun, antonia tarrago and eloisa diaz. join our feminist tour a au tako'a to discover these and more stories hidden in the streets of santiago.Â â € .â €
#feminism #travelrecommendation #travelrecommendations #travelblogger #femaletraveler #metoo #niunamenos #womentraveling

text:
"with a growing number of radio stations wanting to ax the playing of the christmas tune "baby, it's cold outside," someÂ louisville radio stations are fighting backÂ by, you guessed it, playing it, not just from time-to-time, but repeatedly, on a never-ending loop.
classic hits stationÂ waky-fmÂ will be playing "baby, it's cold outside," on a continuous repeating loop beginning sunday morning, said chris randolph, one of the station's disc jockeys. meanwhile, waky, on 103.5 and 100.1 fm, will also be playing different versions of the song over and over for several hours on sunday.
randolph put out this statement:
"everyone just seems so sensitive to the lyrics of the song, & we just thought everybody should calm down," randolph said. "these stations pulling the song, it's absolutely ludicrous."
controversy arose around the christmas tune, written byfrank loesser in 1944, when it started getting banned by radio stations around the country after its lyrics were attacked for promoting date rape & were deemed inappropriate with theÂ #metooÂ movement happening.Â 
however, if the song's detractors were trying to silence and shun it off the airwaves, the exact opposite reaction has happened, with the tune making a comeback in several markets after listeners voted to keep the song on the airwaves. the song is now at close toÂ 11 million views on youtube.
lee cagle, operations manager ofÂ summitmediaÂ says he's "not had one single complaint about the song," adding "i personally think people are looking for things to be offended by." cagle pointed to complaints that another classic christmas tune & film, "rudolph the red-nosed reindeer," features bullying & sexism. "i'm waiting to see which other song people start complaining about," he added. "we don't take life too seriously, & we attract that type of listener," randolph said. "it's all just out of fun.""

classic hits stationÂ waky-fmÂ will be playing "baby, it is cold outside," on a continuous repeating loop beginning sunday morning, said chris randolph, one of the station's disc jockeys. meanwhile, waky, on 103.5 and 100.1 fm, will also be playing different versions of the song over and over for several hours on sunday.
randolph put out this statement:
"everyone just seems so sensitive to the lyrics of the song, & we just thought everybody should calm down," randolph said. "these stations pulling the song, it is absolutely ludicrous."
controversy arose around the christmas tune, written byfrank loesser in 1944, when it started getting banned by radio stations around the country after its lyrics were attacked for promoting date rape & were deemed inappropriate with theÂ #metooÂ movement happening.Â 
however, if the song's detractors were trying to silence and shun it off the airwaves, the exact opposite reaction has happened, with the tune making a comeback in several markets after listeners voted to keep the song on the airwaves. the song is now at close toÂ 11 million views on youtube.
lee cagle, operations manager ofÂ summitmediaÂ says he's "not had one single complaint about the song," adding "i personally think people are looking for things to be offended by." cagle pointed to complaints that another classic christmas tune & film, "rudolph the red-nosed reindeer," features bullying & sexism. "i am waiting to see which other song people start complaining about," he added. "we do not take life too seriously, & we attract that type of listener," randolph said. "it is all just out of fun.""

text: for me looking back, my abuser has been in my life for years. having to realize that nothing was what i thought it was and accepting that every memory of my teenage years is tainted by him weather he was hurting  me or just present for those moments is a painful process. to see your whole high school experience shattered and to not be able to talk about old times because itâ€™s too painful, because he was present for all of them. iâ€™m slowly getting to a point where i can talk about it again sometimes. itâ€™s not easy. do your best . itâ€™s okay if you canâ€™t. just make new beautiful memories without him, in spite of him, the best way to win is to be happy without him. you can do it. i believe in you. #survivorsupport  #metoo #ptsd #pushingforward #takingmypowerback #mymemoriesnotyours

text:
some words, some thoughts... inspired by a conversation i had with @jmhayleypoetry...
.
.
if you feel offended, you is me and maybe you is you as well, maybe not. whatever. .
.
no, i donâ€™t think every abuse or attack can be blamed on men, and neither on women. i believe that itâ€™s very dangerous thing to blame any kind of â€œgroupâ€ and i think we all have our own responsibilities. that doesnâ€™t change the fact that there are horrible people, and that a lot of women have been through horrible things that they can not be blamed for in any kind of way. but it is too easy to blame all men. iâ€™ve seen to many women playing a victim, when they easily could have made other choices, again not always. believe me iâ€™ve come from dark places and i have seen men using their power against a lot of broken girls, but those are not the girls crying for free abortion pills. those are girls crying not even for justice, they are working their ass of while heartbroken just so they can have a new start. .
.
coming up soon is a letter. a letter about feminism and how the #metoo movement is one i no longer want to invest my time in. has feminism become something that i no longer seem to understand? even though i refuse to not believe in equality of the sexes and will always stand for the real definition of feminism. i wonder though; is this movement still about that definition or did it become propaganda; a womanâ€™s cry not for help, but for attention. not for the kind of attention that will help make real, honest and big differences and improve the lives of so many broken and hurt women.. no, just enough attention for their little broken egos to heal. is that todayâ€™s feminism? - also, how much responsibility do we take as women? are we all victims or did we start the games and lost control? .
.
.
.

text:
i can swear, i can joke
i say what's on my mind
if i drink, if i smoke
i keep up with the guys

text:
are you a teen passionate about ending sexual and gender-based violence? 
the firecracker foundation is recruiting self-identified survivors of sexual violence and allies to survivors of sexual violence who are in 10th or 11th grade to its new program, sisters in strength - lansing.  individuals who apply should share a vision for ending violence, desire to build sisterhood/siblinghood (community), and willingness to advocate for change.

link to more information and to apply in the bio.

this is a youth organizing program with a focus on both healing and organizing.

while this program is open to all teen survivors of sexual trauma and their allies, the firecracker foundation will prioritize the applications of teens of color, lgbtq2sia* teens, teens with disabilities and other marginalized groups in the lansing area. 
sisters in strength â€“ lansing is an expansion of the firecracker foundationâ€™s current teen club programming utilizing an adapted version of the sisters in strength (sis) curriculum developed by girls for gender equity - gge, based in brooklyn, new york, and the national me too movement - #metoo. this program is possible through funding provided by the the new york women's foundation and the girls innovate fund and is one of two pilot #metooteen programs in the country.

#metoo #metoomovement #youthorganizer #endsexualviolence
#endgenderbasedviolence 
#sparkhealing #truthtopower #internship #lovelansing #healing #community #opportunity #lgbtq #disabilityjustice #indigineousyouth #latinxyouth [image description: three black teens embrace and smile in white shirts]

text:
self medicating only prolongs your mental healths healing.. .constructive clean healing works alot better xo 
my struggles 26 years ago lost and unsure how to deal with my childhood trauma having constant night terrors and all i wanted was for them to stop.
i wish i found faith and hope sooner which is why i'm here trying to inspire others to live the best versions of themselves and never let a trauma define who you are. you can be who ever you want..! xo

p.s. bititis was my married name years ago but i am no longer married to that person. most of my work i submitted in 2002. i won an award and published in america.

i wish i found faith and hope sooner which is why i am here trying to inspire others to live the best versions of themselves and never let a trauma define who you are. you can be who ever you want..! xo

p.s. bititis was my married name years ago but i am no longer married to that person. most of my work i submitted in 2002. i won an award and published in america.

text:
food justice isnâ€™t just about cleaner watersheds, eradicating factory farming or more $$ in the pockets of the real stewards of the land; small organic and permaculture minded farmers and ranchers.  itâ€™s about  gender equality too, in all realms of this movement.  shout out to @ediblesf for publishing this story.  over the years, i have asked most of the women who have worked in various food service departments at the co-op if they have experienced sexual harassment or discrimination in the greater reno food industry.  not to my surprise, all of the responses sounded a lot like corbina griecoâ€™s when she was interviewed for the edible sf featured article, â€œlike most young women in kitchens i endured by playing along and/or keeping my mouth shut.â€ does that sound familiar?  in order for women to thrive in this male dominated industry we must pretend like things donâ€™t happen. 
things are changing, slowly but surely.  take for instance the james beard restaurant awards... everyone knows that they are a big deal for restaurants across the country, and this year the judges were asked to think a little broader than they have in the past. the judges were asked to,Â â€œwhen considering the candidacy of a person or restaurant, bear in mind that award winners are held up as role models. if you have concerns about a chef, restaurateur or beverage professional, or about the culture around a restaurant or restaurant group, leave the person or business out of your nominations.â€ this as more and more awareness is being drawn to sexual harassment in the restaurant industry. and the result? 40% of nominees were female, up 13% from the year before, where only a quarter of nominations went to female chefs and restauranteurs. @beardfoundation 
if the fundamentals of food systems are going to change then articles like this need to be written, along with one from the james beard foundationâ€™s webpage: â€œwe need to support women in the restaurant industryâ€ - check it out ğŸ¥° (link in bio)

text:
part 2 "trapped in the closet"

so we meet and physically he is not my type. but i tell myself don't judge a book by it's cover. he seemed a little off and nervous. as we sat and talked this guy begins to pull my arm hairs! i'm like don't do that. he says he's sorry and that it's a habit and he plays with his daughter that way. 
i want to run and leave him sitting there, but i ignored my first mind and just said maybe he's being odd because he's nervous. 
so i proceed to date this man. there are a lot of crazy moments with him. there is one where we are almost killed by a speeding car some loser carjacked. then there is the time where i met his crazy narcissistic cop sister. but what i'm writing about now is when he made me get in a closet and forced me not to come out. 
i had no idea that his elderly mother was home and he had invited me to spend the night. day came and it's a few days before christmas. his cop sister wants him to go shopping. this guy grabs me out of bed, tells me quickly my mom doesn't know you are here, get your ass in the closet and stay there until i get back. 
#metoo #abusiverelationship #bipolar #bipolardisorder #storytimethread #storytime

text:
@regran_ed from @galaxy4peace -  earlier today, we joined @awloint and @yalinetworklag on the #womendecide awareness walk to raise awareness and discuss issues around women's participation in politics. 
____________
to change the narratives, there is urgent need to accelerate equal participation of women in decision-making in the household and at the community level through adequate enlightenment, beginning at a tender age and making sure to reach the grassroots level so that no one is left behind.

and to promote womenâ€™s participation as voters and candidates in electoral processes and supporting womenâ€™s representation in governance institutions, including constitutional committees, electoral offices, public administrations, galaxy4peace strongly calls for more collaboration of stakeholders to develop and implement advocacy strategies, and policies that will facilitate in changing the narratives.

text:
part 3
"trapped in the closet"

so he forces me in the closet and tells me to stay in there until he gets back. i insist that i want to just leave. he twists my arm and tells me don't fucking come out, he loves me and he'll be back and closes the door. once i'm in i'm to scared and shocked to even make a noise. this side of him came out of nowhere. 
i'm in the closet and i'm scared, i have to pee. i try not to move so no one hears me. i feel if his mother hears me she will be frightened. k also am scared that if he finds out he could really hurt me. 
time passes and i noticed the day turns to night. i can tell through a small crack in the door. suddenly i hear footsteps coming up stairs, the bedroom door opens. i freeze, too scared to breathe. it was him. he slowly opens the door. "aww poot" he says with a weird grin calling me my nickname he gave me. "come out pootie". he grabs me by my wrist and walks me slowly out of the closet. i start crying, without making a sound. i see i had been in that closet for 7 hours..7 insane hours!! he kisses me on the forehead and makes me sit down on the bed. i say i have to use the bathroom. he frowns and says bring your ass on. he sneaks me downstairs to the bathroom. 
after this twisted event i end up stuck spending christmas there. i will share next time how that went.

#bipolarrelationship #metoo #abuse #abusiverelationship #mentalillness #storytimethread #storytime #realshit #reallife #bipolar #bipolardisorder

text:
hello everyone, i am sorry i haven't been as active since being released from the hospital. i elected to admit myself to a partial hospitalization program and intensive outpatient program to better help me in my adjustment from the hospital, for further management of my medications, and to better process my trauma. i want to make sure this remains a space where i post because i feel like i have something valuable to contribute, not out of obligation. i am trying not to feel guilty and just respect that i need and deserve self care right now.

thank you all for your lovely and supportive messages. also, if you have sent me a dm and haven't gotten a response it is nothing personal at all. i receive many messages, most of which include disclosures of some kind. for the sake of my own mental health i respond when i am in the best place of mind to do so. the fact that people trust me with their trauma is incredible, humbling and not something i take lightly. you are all so incredibly strong and inspiring to me. 
comment below: what was your favorite lesson? what is your biggest lesson(s) learned as a survivor? 
leave a ğŸ’œ if you read this far.

thank you all for your lovely and supportive messages. also, if you have sent me a dm and have not gotten a response it is nothing personal at all. i receive many messages, most of which include disclosures of some kind. for the sake of my own mental health i respond when i am in the best place of mind to do so. the fact that people trust me with their trauma is incredible, humbling and not something i take lightly. you are all so incredibly strong and inspiring to me. 
comment below: what was your favorite lesson? what is your biggest lesson(s) learned as a survivor?

text:
thank you to the men who joined voices.
@regran_ed from @morlahdey -  do more for your community!!! on the 15th of december, 2018 we the member of @yalinetworklag in collaboration with @awloint matched out to create and sensitize ikeja community at the early hour of yesterday on the involvement and participation of passionate women in #leadership while we also discuss about our #9javotes2019 campaign awareness activities.

#womendecide is the theme because it's high time passionate women leaders get involved massively in nation development through different platforms that will enhance their leadership skills.

#9javotes2019 by yali lagos is another activities we engage ourselves, so as to learn more about our dear country 2019 forthcoming elections and most importantly on how patriotic citizens should get involved in the electioneering process without violence, selling of vote etc.

while on our way back home, few of us also join #stoprape #stopwomenviolence campaign awareness by some fellow young leaders around shoprite nigeria in ikeja axis to kick against rape and domestic violence that higher percentage of women in our society are always a victim.

let's keep doing more for humanity.

#moreglobal #yalinetwork #awlo - #regrann

@regran_ed from @badasscrossstitch -  via @cnn - cyntoia brown, who's serving life in prison for killing a man who bought her for sex when she was 16, could still be freed soon.
the tennessee supreme court last week ruled brown would have to serve at least 51 years in prison for the 2004 killing before she's eligible for release.
but amid widespread outrage on social media, gov. bill haslam's office is now reviewing her case. <â€”â€”- proof that we can have a voice and impact. â€”â€”-
what to do now? 
1. go read about the case
2. sign the moveon petition 
3. share your thoughts and links on social media so folks know and can take action 
4. contact gov bill haslamâ€™s office and voice your thoughts 1st floor, state capitol nashville, tn 37243 (615) 741-2001 
5. his instagram @governorbillhaslam (remember, he is considering clemency so letâ€™s honor and encourage that) 
6. watch the video: me facing life: cyntoiaâ€™s story - google it - itâ€™s on @pbs and you can watch it online. â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”

text: last friday i had the came back for a second serving of the inheritance part 2, one of the theatrical events of the year if you happen to live in london (and especially if you happen to be part of the lgbt+ community). one of the highlights of course is getting to see the legendary vanessa redgrave up close in the playâ€™s only female role, performing a good many times a week at age eighty. i had the chance to see redgrave at the bfi a couple of months ago when she introduced tom jones, directed by her then husband tony richardson. whilst the film remains one of those oscar oddities that has not aged particularly well, it was great to see vanessa reminiscing about that time in the british cinema industry and what it was like to be part of the woodfall troupe of filmmakers (including stories of working methods that would not stand up to scrutiny in the #metoo era). #vanessaredgrave #tomjones #oscars #britishtalent #uk #londonculture #theinheritance #stars #culture #fashion #silverscreen #london #celluloid  #divas #celebrity #celebrities #hollywood #oldhollywood ##influencer #film #filmgeek #filmcritic #ilovefilm #culture #cinephile #cinephilecommunity

text:
i don't know how but i have made it through this week! i am exhausted as my sleep has been shocking, my headaches ongoing and feeling worse by the day, my anxiety has been frustrating and chronic pain issues have had massive swings between good and bad days. not to mention feeling sick and the night terrors linger through the days at time, trying to analyze it or it triggers flashbacks... what can i do?
..
i am putting on a brave face because i don't have a choice really. i can't change what happened last year and how i got to where i am now. life is what it is and i just have to take each day as it comes, be grateful for what i have, even though i feel i could break down and cry at any moment. ..

text:
i am powerfully rooted in the earth, reaching towards the heavens. through the ages i may rise and fall, forever transcending, always connected to the stillness within. 
__________________
the journey has been long; i have lived many lives. discovering my truth, reconciling past karma, honoring my soul. 
__________________
i have learned to forgive those who stole my innocence, defiled my body and bruised my soul. i am a wise warrior who does not fear labels or judgement because i own the strength of my truth. 
__________________
i am here to serve and yet i belong to no one. you are me - i am you - we are one. 
__________________
do not admire my power, as it is also yours. 
__________________
ego climbs the mountain ~ the soul -is- the mountain. release the ego - stand tall as you embrace your soulâ€™s truth and flow into divine stillness.
__________________

text:
@keiko_conservation last month, 10 indonesian fishermen working on a japanese longline vessel were caught trying to smuggle 962 #sharkfins in their luggage through honolulu airport. now, five more have been charged, including the two businesses that have ownership of the boat and three of the japanese crew (the captain, fishing master, and first engineer).
according to court documents, all three permitted discarding the shark carcasses and possessing then transporting the fins. the first engineer explicitly directed the indonesian #fishermen to cut off the fins and package some of the fins for himself and the chief officer to take with them after they disembarked. the fishing master, toshiyuki komatsu, ordered the fishermen to not cut the line and release the shark alive as it would mean losing the fishing rigged line and hook. instead he ordered them to kill the sharks or intentionally weaken them to retrieve them. the fishermen admitted that they sometimes cut the line anyways when the fishing master was not looking because they were afraid they would be injured by one of the sharks. the three were not arrested and considered at large, most likely home in japan, but face a maximum fine of $2.75 million each. bringing the fins back to japan would mean they also broke #japanese law by retaining ocean white tip sharks and #silkysharks , both of which are protected species, and by not landing the sharks whole before finning them.
the sharks were most likely fished during their longline tuna #fishing efforts in the southern eastern pacific ocean, ene of #tahiti, approximately a third of the way between tahiti towards mexico. it is estimated 300 #sharks were harvested
more details as well as the court documents can be found on our website (direct page linked in ig story). keikoconservation. say no to #sharkfinsoup #shark second photo illustration credit from @saving.oceans #respectlife #loveanimals #letthembe #theirlivesmatter #lovethemall #animallovers #animalkingdom #familyiseverything #savetheocean #savetheearth #peaceandlove #govegan #crueltyfree #environment #environmentalist #planetearth #metoo #wildlife #wildlife_perfection #donttakeourplanetforgranted

when i was 14 i was manipulated by an â€œemployerâ€ who tried to assault me. when i thought i saw him at school, my safe place, i broke down in the stairwell. one of my classmates found me, and he took me to the guidance counselor who brought in a social worker every week to help me learn to cope. â–

there are little things, though, like when a man in a passing vehicle cat called me, and i had the audacity to give him an obscene gesture. so he parked and stalked me through the grocery store. i was terrified. â–

but sometimes, itâ€™s the big things, like when i reached my mid-twenties and suddenly had every adult manifestation of childhood sexual abuse. i can see the flashbacks and relive the pain, but at such a young age, i learned to disassociate from the experience. to this day, i still canâ€™t see the perpetratorâ€™s face. â–

so call it #metoo or whatever you want, but iâ€™m more than a statistic. i own my demons and they canâ€™t hurt me anymore. â–

powerlifting might just be a sport to some, but itâ€™s my therapy. it develops my mental fortitude to push through every day and gives me the strength to know that i will never let anyone hurt me like that again. â–
@davidgoggins

text:
today's inspirator is @justinbaldoni. justin baldoni is an american actor, director, and social entrepreneur. justin who not everyone would say looks like it, has gone through the phase of negative self body image. he talks a lot about this in the manenough episode - "the ugliness of body image" on metoo. in the beginning he states that even though in his movies and shoots he constantly has his shirt off, he still has insecurities about his body. he also feels that what he does, makes other men uncomfortable in their own bodies. just because a man is taking off their shirt, it doesn't always mean they're not insecure. every man has insecurities, but they should never look at other people bodies and aspire to be like that. your body is your body, no one should ever tell you to gain weight, lose weight, get muscles, or grow facial hair to be a "real" man. justin baldoni also makes an appearance on ted talk for why i'm done trying to be "man enough." he goes more in depth about his conflict between how he felt vs what the world was telling he should be as man. society saw him to be this strong man with charisma and power, however he didn't feel that way about himself. he felt like he was pretending to be someone he wasn't. feeling weak and insecure, but pretended to be strong and confident. he acted rough but deep down was hurting, he was just so tired of having to be "man enough" for everyone. why did he have to hide the truth? why did he have to put himself through that, when he could of came out and asked for help. it's not easy. men all around the world are going through the exact same thing, and they can't speak for themselves because it's hard. together we can help them, just like justin baldoni.

and eventually it comes out in a tidal wave of repression, anger and fear. 
making the right choice everything changes.

we feel safe. 
weâ€™re not too much and all the weirdness and kookiness and too muchness can just be.

we donâ€™t have to worry about texts not coming fast enough or whatâ€™s going on at all times.

text:
no one ever asks what made you gain weight.
.
i never thought iâ€™d be brave enough to share this part of my life.
.
though this is painful to share, i know we are stronger when we talk about our struggles-and i hope you will share yours with me below. (#metoo)
.
when i was 21 i was slipped a date-rape drug. 
the remaining details are not significant to my story, but something was taken from me that night that iâ€™ll never get back.
.
the final words i was left with were â€œi only gave you what you deservedâ€...which were words that pierced my heart and mind for many years to come.
.
what i...deserved???
.
i immediately turned to food for comfort. honestly, the more weight i gained-the safer i felt. i felt like if i was overweight, no one would find me attractive and i wouldnâ€™t ever get hurt again.
.
but the weight that i carried pierced much deeper.
.
instead of dealing with it, i tucked it away in my mind and hoped i would never have to face it. i started eating my feelings instead...
.
the sad reality is: 1 in 6 women will be a victim of sexual assault/rape. and itâ€™s something we donâ€™t talk about. at least i didnâ€™t for many years. it was a secret i hid from the world because i felt so ashamed.
.
nobody is deserving of that. nobody. and it took me many years to fully believe that.
.
i didnâ€™t take care of myself anymore...
i didnâ€™t love myself anymore...
food was the only comfort that i had...
the thought of taking it away made me uncomforable.
.
but i took my life back...and so can you.
.
i share this with you, because i know iâ€™m not alone. many of us had an event that triggered us to gain weight. but the beautiful thing is: you have the power within you to overcome it.
.
we are not defined by our past. 
we are not what had happened to us. 
we have the power to design a bright future and never look back. 
we have nothing to be ashamed of.
.
our trials can become our triumphs.
our tests can become our testimony. 
our messes can become our message.
.
and i know that if i can overcome my struggles...so can you.
.

text:
some people come in our lives to love us,

some come in our lives to rob us of our dignity, pride and prized possessions

some come in our lives with lessons to change our life

but once in a while comes a special someone who makes you feel a little different, a little loved and most of all make us see the goodness in us.

with his eyes i saw goodness in me, which i once thought was robbed, looted and exploited. before he came i was something else, something close to a pessimist. someone who was ready to throw herself off the cliff, but fate had something else. he never demanded a change. he loved all formes of me- even the sad, broken and devastated version of me. my broken heart used to hurt a lot, which i never thought could be reversed. but his love was like magic. he made me feel beautiful again, made me believe that i was worthy of being loved again. and most of all, made me believe that i could love again.

he made me believe that i wasnâ€™t any empty vessel, i still had endless love to offer. he changed me, without even asking me to change. he came in my life when i was at my lowest, and with him, i have only risen higher.

with him, i find it easier to battle my negatively,

with him, i realized i was never a salve to this society, but i was trapped in the cage built inside my mind. he liberated me of all burdens.

with him, i find in myself a little more strength to combat depression,

with him, i believe in myself a little more,

with him, i fear a little less and love a little moreâ€¦
.
- a tribute to raju jana @iam_awsm
.
(- from khushboo rani mahato @this_chick_writes)
.
--------Ã—--------
.
in these times of #metoo and stories of sexual harassment, there are also women and men around us who made us feel more beautiful, more confident and powerful from both inside and out. 
if there is a person who brought some meaningful changes in your life, then let's pay a tribute to her/him right here at @shespeaksforthechange.

we all need such people around us afterall, don't we?

some people come in our lives to love us,

some come in our lives to rob us of our dignity, pride and prized possessions

some come in our lives with lessons to change our life

but once in a while comes a special someone who makes you feel a little different, a little loved and most of all make us see the goodness in us.

with his eyes i saw goodness in me, which i once thought was robbed, looted and exploited. before he came i was something else, something close to a pessimist. someone who was ready to throw herself off the cliff, but fate had something else. he never demanded a change. he loved all formes of me- even the sad, broken and devastated version of me. my broken heart used to hurt a lot, which i never thought could be reversed. but his love was like magic. he made me feel beautiful again, made me believe that i was worthy of being loved again. and most of all, made me believe that i could love again.

he made me believe that i wasnâ€™t any empty vessel, i still had endless love to offer. he changed me, without even asking me to change. he came in my life when i was at my lowest, and with him, i have only risen higher.

with him, i find it easier to battle my negatively,

with him, i realized i was never a salve to this society, but i was trapped in the cage built inside my mind. he liberated me of all burdens.

with him, i find in myself a little more strength to combat depression,

with him, i believe in myself a little more,

with him, i fear a little less and love a little moreâ€¦
.
- a tribute to raju jana @iam_awsm
.
(- from khushboo rani mahato @this_chick_writes)
.

if there is a person who brought some meaningful changes in your life, then let's pay a tribute to her/him right here at @shespeaksforthechange.

we all need such people around us afterall, do not we?
